This diversity of studies in the two authors before us has given a widely different character to their writings. In one we have the impassioned declaimer, in the other the uncom- promising moralist. Persius, though he borrowed much of the language of Horace, has little of his manner. The im- mediate object of his imitation appears to be Lucilius.
